graph TD

  subgraph Generalists
    g1[Definition: UX designers with a broad range of responsibilities.]
    g2[Responsibilities: Varied tasks such as interaction design, visual design, user research, branding, prototyping, and more.]
    g3[Common at: Smaller companies with fewer design departments.]
    g4[Benefits: Opportunity to try various roles, find a specialty, and continue learning on the job.]
  end

  subgraph Specialists
    s1[Definition: UX designers who dive deep into one specific UX design role (e.g., interaction, visual, or motion design).]
    s2[Responsibilities: Focus on a specific area, providing more in-depth knowledge.]
    s3[Common at: Larger companies with the resources for specialized roles.]
    s4[Example: Google has thousands of specialized UX designers.]
  end

  subgraph T-Shaped Designers
    t1[Definition: UX designers with specialization in one area and a breadth of knowledge in other areas.]
    t2[Skills: Uppercase T represents specialization (vertical line) and complementary skills (horizontal line).]
    t3[Advancement: Typically occurs as a designer advances in their career and gains diverse experience.]
    t4[Benefits: Broader perspective, exposure to different companies, design principles, and work styles.]
  end

  subgraph Career_Progression
    c1[Choices: Generalist or specialist roles may be influenced by workplace needs.]
    c2[Example: Personal experience of transitioning from a motion graphics designer to a focus on privacy as an interaction designer at Google.]
    c3[Opportunities: Continuous growth and opportunities for change in the dynamic field of UX design.]
  end

  g1 --> g2 --> g3 --> g4
  s1 --> s2 --> s3 --> s4
  t1 --> t2 --> t3 --> t4
  c1 --> c2 --> c3

